Introduction

The Covid-19 pandemic has generated a wide range of reactions and opinions, as evident on Twitter. The spread of misinformation has become a challenge in public health, and as such, this project aims to use Natural Language Processing techniques to identify those tweets that carry misinformation.

The Dataset

The dataset used here comes from research at the Center for Machine Learning and Health at Carnegie Mellon University. The data itself, whilst derived from public postings, is itself privately held, so is not available to share in full.

The data was gathered via the Twitter API using several hashtag keywords relating to the pandemic as later mentioned. The data was then manually annotated into 17 categories based on their content.

Preprocessing and Feature Engineering

Throughout this report, features will be engineered with the goal of creating a misinformation classifier. Some of these features are added to the dataset along the way, whereas others will be engineered later based on exploration of the data as broader categories.

Tokenization

The tweets data is tokenized using the TweetTokenizer from the Natural Language ToolKit (NLTK). Here, the reduce_len parameter is used to reduce repeated characters, e.g. 'funnnnnnn' to 'funnn' - this is decided as both of these strings have the same meaning.

In [9]:
# Tokenize tweets (code adapted from https://towardsdatascience.com/an-introduction-to-tweettokenizer-for-processing-tweets-9879389f8fe7)
from nltk.tokenize import TweetTokenizer
# Initialise the tokenizer
tokenizer = TweetTokenizer(reduce_len = True)

data['tokens'] = data['text'].map(lambda x: tokenizer.tokenize(x))

Weblinks

The weblinks in each tweet are each likely going to be different - however, when analysing these, the presence of a link to an external site may hold information about e.g. a referenced response. These are substituted out to uniformly represent a link as 'http'.

In [11]:
token_nl = list()
for tweet in data['tokens']:
    tweet_nl = list()
    for token in tweet:
        tweet_nl.append(
            re.sub('http.*', 'http', token)
        )
    token_nl.append(tweet_nl)
data['tokens'] = token_nl

It is useful to see the progress so far by looking at what the most common words/tokens are.

[('.', 4488), ('the', 3669), (',', 3191), ('to', 2759), ('http', 2479), ('a', 2174), ('and', 1997), ('is', 1792), ('of', 1625), ('covid', 1514), ('coronavirus', 1216), ('it', 1189), ('you', 1169), ('-', 1166), ('@user', 1162), ('in', 1111), ('’', 1085), ('for', 1074), ('that', 1018), ('19', 952)]

We observe that many of the most common tokens have little meaning. The punctuation and stopwords are removed from our data, and tokens are all lowercased for uniformity and to avoid later duplication of tokens in a vectorizer with Capitalised and lowercase formats.

Punctuation is removed, and both a prebuilt stopwords lexicon is used to remove stopwords as well as a user-defined list:

  • '19' is removed, as this is likely used where 'covid' and '19' have been split - the '19' holds no extra information, so is removed
  • 'http' is now removed, as they hold little intrinsic meaning, and the count has already been saved as a feature
In [14]:
# import nltk
# nltk.download('stopwords')
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

my_stops = [
    '19',
    'http'
]

tokens_lcns = list()
for tweet in data['tokens']:
    clean_tweet = list()
    for token in tweet:
        token = token.lower()
        if token not in (stopwords.words('english') + my_stops):
            match = re.match('#.*', str(token))
            if (match != None) | token.isalpha(): # Remove punctuation (is alphabetical) (Code from https://towardsdatascience.com/text-normalization-for-natural-language-processing-nlp-70a314bfa646)
                clean_tweet.append(token)
    tokens_lcns.append(clean_tweet)

Simple Metrics - ?,!,#,@

The original number of question and exclamation marks may be informative in distinguishing misinformation. However, these measures will be calculated per sentence, as a tweet with more sentences is inherently going to be more likely to contain more punctuation, including exclamation and question marks.

In [18]:
# nltk.download('punkt')
from nltk.tokenize import sent_tokenize

quest_count = list()
exclam_count = list()

for tweet in data['text']:
    sent_count = len(sent_tokenize(str(tweet)))
    quest = round( len(re.findall('\?', tweet)) / sent_count , 2)
    exclam = round( len(re.findall('!', tweet)) / sent_count , 2)
    quest_count.append(quest)
    exclam_count.append(exclam)

data['question_dens'] = quest_count
data['exclam_dens'] = exclam_count

Hashtags

The tokens still contain hashtags, including those used to filter the tweets' text. The hashtag are separated from the tweets as they are not part of the central message, but are still relevant.

According to Twitter (https://business.twitter.com/en/blog/how-to-create-and-use-hashtags.html), hashtags are not case-sensitive, meaning #CoronaVirus and #coronavirus will deliver the same output. Therefore, we can lowercase everything here for simplicity, including the hashtags used to gather the tweets.

In [21]:
my_tags = r'(#nCoV20199)|(#CoronaOutbreak)|(#CoronaVirus)|(#CoronavirusCoverup)|(#CoronavirusOutbreak)|(#COVID19)|(#Coronavirus)|(#WuhanCoronavirus)|(#coronaviris)|(#Wuhan)'.lower(
)

tokens_nh = list()
any_hash = list()
not_my_hash = list()

for tweet in data['tokens']:

    tweet_any_hash = list()
    tweet_not_my_hash = list()
    tweet_clean = list()
    
    for token in tweet:

        any_match = re.match('#.*', str(token))

        if (any_match != None): # A hashtag was found
            tweet_any_hash.append(token)
            my_match = re.match(my_tags, str(token))
            if (my_match == None): # It was not one of my hashtags found
                tweet_not_my_hash.append(token)
        else: # No hashtag found
            tweet_clean.append(token)

    
    any_hash.append(tweet_any_hash)
    not_my_hash.append(tweet_not_my_hash)
    tokens_nh.append(tweet_clean)

data['tokens'] = tokens_nh
data['all_hash'] = any_hash
data['other_hash'] = not_my_hash

Looking at tweet 1 below, we see tokens no longer contain hashtags, all hashtags are saved under 'all_hash', with the non-filter hashtags additionally under 'other_hash'.

# Find distribution of POS

from collections import defaultdict
category_count = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['type']) # Create empty dataframe

for cat in data['category'].unique(): # Iterate through each category

    cat_data = data[data['category'] == cat]
    pos_type = defaultdict(int) # Code adapted from https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python-increment-value-in-dictionary/

    for tweet in cat_data['pos']: # Iterate through each tweet
        for tok,tag in tweet: # Iterate through each token and POS tag, save each POS count to dictionary
            pos_type['count'] += 1 # Save the total number of POS tags per category
            pos_type[tag] += 1
    cat_df = pd.DataFrame()
    for dic in pos_type:
        row = pd.Series({dic: pos_type[dic]})
        cat_df = pd.concat([cat_df, row])

    cat_df.columns = [cat]

    category_count = category_count.join(cat_df, on='type', how='outer')

category_count['Total'] = category_count.sum(axis=1) # Find row totals
category_count = category_count.sort_values(by='Total', ascending=False) # Sort by totals

We can see that the distributions of word types vary across the categories (using the most common word types in the corpus). Some noticeable differences are:

  • Fake cures and commercials use more singular nouns (NN)
  • Fake cures and Fake treaments use fewer present tense verbs (VBP)
  • Adverbs (RB) are less common in News, Emergency, and True public health response
  • News uses fewer verbs (VB)

These evident differences alone show promise for a fake news classifier. One thing to note is that the 'False public health response' category only had 35 tokens in it, so the dearth of data in this category makes it less reliable - this also contributes to the white spaces in the heatmap where there was no data found.

Similarities between Categories' Vocabulary

To examine the vocabulary similarities between categories, the errors between category proportions is found - those categories with the lowest pairwise error should indicate those with the most similar POS distribution, and therefore the most similar vocabulary.

In [28]:
category_error = pd.DataFrame()
cat_count = len(category_prop.columns)

for col_a in range(cat_count):
    for col_b in range(cat_count):
        if col_a > col_b:
            diff = (category_prop.iloc[:, col_a] -
                    category_prop.iloc[:, col_b])
            diff_error = np.sqrt(np.mean(diff * diff))
            category_error.loc[str(category_prop.columns[col_a]),
                               str(category_prop.columns[col_b])] = diff_error
sns.set(rc={'axes.facecolor': 'khaki'})
plt.title('Heatmap of RMSE of proportions between categories', fontsize=20)

Top 3 Hashtags

To find the top 3 hashtags for each category, a slightly different method needs to be used compared with the previous section. This is due to each hashtag needing counting separately. Where each category doesn't have a distinct top 3 (e.g. where 3rd place is tied between several hashtags), these should be identified as co-third place where appropriate.

In [34]:
all_top_hash = pd.DataFrame()
other_top_hash = pd.DataFrame()

for cat in data['category'].unique():  # Iterate through each category
#     cat_data = data[data['category'] == cat]

    for hash_cols in [
            'all_hash', 'other_hash'
    ]:  # Execute for both 'all hashtags' and 'excluding filtered hashtags'
        ao_hash_dic = defaultdict(int)
        for hash_list in data[data['category'] == cat][hash_cols]:  # Iterate through each tweet
#         for hash_list in cat_data[hash_cols]:  # Iterate through each tweet
            for each_hash in hash_list:  # Iterate through each hashtag
                ao_hash_dic[str(each_hash)] += 1  # Count each hashtag

            # Convert dictionary counts to a dataframe
            ao_hash_df = pd.DataFrame()
            for dic in ao_hash_dic:
                ao_hash_df.loc[dic, 'Count'] = ao_hash_dic[dic]

        if (ao_hash_df.empty == False):  # Check the dataframe isn't empty
            ao_hash_df = ao_hash_df.sort_values(by='Count', ascending=False)
            ao_hash_df.index.name = 'Hash'
            ao_hash_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
            ao_hash_df = ao_hash_df.iloc[0:8, :]  # Take the top 7 rows - this is more than the 3 required, but 3rd place may be tied
            ao_hash_df['Category'] = cat
            if (hash_cols == 'all_hash'):
                all_top_hash = pd.concat([all_top_hash, ao_hash_df])
            else:
                other_top_hash = pd.concat([other_top_hash, ao_hash_df])

Sentiment Analysis

Sentiment analysis may be useful to compare differences between categories. The two methods used here are split into:

  • Affect analysis - Positive/Negative sentiment
  • Emotional analysis - Emotional categorisation of sentiment

Affect Analysis - VADER

VADER (Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiment Reasoner) is used for affect analysis, as it is particularly effective for use on tweets. This is due to the lexicon containing slang and words specific to social-media.

VADER uses a lexicon that finds the polarity of a sentiment (positive/negative) and the intensity of the emotion (https://towardsdatascience.com/sentimental-analysis-using-vader-a3415fef7664). This is therefore built on a 2-dimensional theory of emotions: valence = pleasantness and arousal=intensity (Russell, J. A. (1980) 'A circumplex model of affect', Journal of Personality and Social Psychology).

The VADER technique gives simple affect scoring split between positive, negative and neutral (totalling 1), with a compound score (from -1 to 1) representing these scores as a single normalised value. Code adapted from https://realpython.com/python-nltk-sentiment-analysis/.

VADER takes raw strings as inputs. Whilst the tweets in their original form could be used as inputs, having tested this, this tends to increase the 'neutral' score. This indicates that removal of stopwords and the other preprocessing so far has removed some of the less meaningful content from the corpus.

Once VADER scoring has been determined, due to 'positive + negative + neutral' scores for each category adding to 1, we can plot positive sentiment against negative for each category to see how they differ between categories.

In [37]:
# nltk.download('vader_lexicon')
from nltk.sentiment import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer

affect_scores = pd.DataFrame()
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
for cat in data['category'].unique():
    strings_tok = str(data[data['category'] == cat]['tokens'])
    affect_scores.loc[cat,
                      'Positive'] = sia.polarity_scores(strings_tok)['pos']
    affect_scores.loc[cat,
                      'Negative'] = sia.polarity_scores(strings_tok)['neg']
affect_scores.index.name = 'Category'
affect_scores.reset_index(inplace=True)

ax = sns.scatterplot(data=affect_scores,
                     x='Positive',
                     y='Negative',
                     palette='rocket',
                     s=200)
for i in range(0, len(affect_scores)):
    adjust_x = 0.0018
    adjust_y = 0.0004
    ax.annotate(affect_scores['Category'][i],
                xy=(affect_scores['Positive'][i] + adjust_x,
                    affect_scores['Negative'][i] + adjust_y),
                fontsize=13,
                rotation=20)
plt.title('Sentiment Analysis Affect Scores of each Category', fontsize=20)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Whilst there is some bunching of categories in the plot, it is apparent that even a simple 2-score affect analysis could help to distinguish the categories. For example, 'false fact or prevention' is clearly separate from the rest, with a high Positive score and a medium Negative score.
Also, somewhat ironically, 'Ambiguous or hard to classify' is also distinct, with a medium Positive score and a high Negative score. However, it should be noted that there is no indication of the overlap/spread of each category as measured this way, due to analysing the corpus by whole category rather than by tweet and category.

Emotional Analysis - NRCLex

To attempt to improve on the affect analysis for later classification, it is worth examining a more comprehensive scoring system and applying it to each tweet. These scores can be determined for each tweet, and averaged across each category to compare results.

NRCLex uses a similar lexicon-based method to VADER, but applies scoring across 10 emotional classes. As this requires a string as an input and ignores any non-matches to the lexicon, we can safely apply this to the original tweet text without the scores being affected by any meaningless words/tokens present. Code adapted from https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/emotion-classification-using-nrc-lexicon-in-python/.

NB: Whilst these new emotional scores are being saved to the dataset, the positive and negative VADER scores will be saved also.

In [38]:
# ! pip install NRCLex
from nrclex import NRCLex

for stat_id in range(0, 1+max(data['status_id'])): # Iterate through each tweet
    sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer() # Initialise VADER
    sia = sia.polarity_scores(str(data.loc[stat_id,'tokens'])) # Apply VADER to tokenised/preprocessed text
    emotion = NRCLex(data.loc[stat_id,'text']) # Apply NRCLex to original tweet text
    # Save VADER output
    data.loc[stat_id,'Sent_Pos'] = sia['pos']
    data.loc[stat_id,'Sent_Neg'] = sia['neg']
    
    # Save NRCLex output
    for each in emotion.affect_frequencies:
        lex_head = 'Lex_' + str(each)
        if each == 'anticip': # Bug in NRCLex sometimes mislabels this emotion
            lex_head = 'Lex_anticipation'
        data.loc[stat_id, lex_head] = emotion.affect_frequencies[each]

The heatmap shows some distinction between categories for the top 10 POS tags. However, these are based on logged proportions, whereas the actual counts per category start to get quite low beyond the top 6 POS tags, considering the number of tweets.

The earlier POS tag distribution graph shows how the prevalence of POS tags decreases rapidly, with the top 4 tags comprising approximately 40%, 20%, 10%, and 5% of all tags respectively. A more useful and reliable metric may be drawn from combining some of the POS categories. In [47]:
nouns = ['NN', 'NNP', 'NNPS', 'NNS']
verbs = ['VB', 'VBD', 'VBG', 'VBN', 'VBP', 'VBZ']
adjs = ['JJ', 'JJR', 'JJS']

for i in range(0, len(data)):
    tweet = data.loc[i,'pos']
    pos_type = defaultdict(int)
    for tok,tag in tweet: # Iterate through each token and POS tag, save each POS count to dictionary
        pos_type['count'] += 1 # Save the total number of POS tags per category
        pos_type[tag] += 1
    
    if pos_type['count'] == 0: # No tags found
        data.loc[i,'noun_prop'] = 0
        data.loc[i,'verb_prop'] = 0
        data.loc[i,'adj_prop'] = 0
        data.loc[i,'noun_verb'] = 0
        data.loc[i,'adj_verb'] = 0        
    else:
        group_counts = defaultdict(int)
        for noun in nouns: # Count nouns
            group_counts['nouns'] += pos_type[noun]
        for verb in verbs: # Count verbs
            group_counts['verbs'] += pos_type[verb]
        for adj in adjs: # Count adjectives
            group_counts['adjs'] += pos_type[adj]
        noun_prop = group_counts['nouns'] / pos_type['count']
        verb_prop = group_counts['verbs'] / pos_type['count']
        adj_prop = group_counts['adjs'] / pos_type['count']
        
        verb_prop_adjusted = verb_prop
        if verb_prop == 0:
            verb_prop_adjusted = 1 # Ensures no division by 0
        
        nouns_to_verbs = noun_prop / verb_prop_adjusted
        adjs_to_verbs = adj_prop / verb_prop_adjusted
        
        data.loc[i,'noun_prop'] = noun_prop
        data.loc[i,'verb_prop'] = verb_prop
        data.loc[i,'adj_prop'] = adj_prop
        data.loc[i,'noun_verb'] = nouns_to_verbs
        data.loc[i,'adj_verb'] = adjs_to_verbs

Target Labelling

There are currently 16 categories of tweets. The goal here is to identify misinformation, so these can be merged where appropriate to give 'misinfo' and 'no-misinfo' labels.

It is apparent that 'fake cure', 'conspiracy', 'false fact or prevention', 'fake treatment', and 'false public health response' are the categories of the 'misinfo' label.

In [48]:
misinfo = ['fake cure', 'conspiracy', 'false fact or prevention', 'fake treatment', 'false public health response']

for cat in misinfo:
    for i in range(0, len(data)):
        if data.loc[i,'category'] == cat:
            data.loc[i,'label'] = 'misinfo'

The no-misinfo categories will be 'irrelevant', 'politics', 'true public health response', 'news', 'calling out or correction', 'true prevention', 'commercial activity or promotion', and 'emergency'. Whilst not all of these are relevant to Covid-19, they are not themselves misinformation.

Noticeably, the 'sarcasm or satire', 'ambiguous or hard to classify', and 'panic buying' categories are not included. A sarcastic tweet could be inferring information or misinformation, so it is unclear which of these labels would apply. Ambiguous tweets again suffer the same problem. Panic buying tweets could be interpreted either way - misinformation due to promoting unnecessary purchasing, or a factual statement that panic buying has occurred. Again, which label it should have is unclear, so it is left out of our dataset.

In [49]:
no_misinfo = ['irrelevant', 'politics', 'true public health response', 'news', 'calling out or correction', 'true prevention', 'commercial activity or promotion', 'emergency']
for cat in no_misinfo:
    for i in range(0, len(data)):
        if data.loc[i,'category'] == cat:
            data.loc[i,'label'] = 'no_misinfo'

count_train_df = pd.DataFrame(count_train.todense(), columns=count_vectorizer.get_feature_names())

X_train.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)
X_train_c = pd.concat([X_train, count_train_df], axis=1)

count_test_df = pd.DataFrame(count_test.todense(), columns=count_vectorizer.get_feature_names())

from imblearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Specify steps of pipeline
c_steps = [('mnb', MultinomialNB())]
# Construct the pipeline
c_pipe = Pipeline(c_steps)
# Decide ranges of parameters to use
parameters = {
    'mnb__alpha': np.linspace(0.1,1,10)
}
# Set up cross-validation of the pipeline (5-fold chosen, and n_jobs allows parallel processing)
mnb_cv = GridSearchCV(c_pipe, parameters, cv=5, n_jobs=-2, scoring='accuracy')
# Fit GridSearch object to the training data
_ = mnb_cv.fit(X_train_OS,y_train_OS)

# Use model to assess fit on the training set and predict on the test set
y_pred_train = mnb_cv.predict(X_train_OS)
y_pred = mnb_cv.predict(X_test_c)
# Show recall figure of prediction model and predictions from training set
print('Training set accuracy score of naive bayes classifier: {:.2f}'.format(accuracy_score(y_train_OS, y_pred_train)))
print('Test set accuracy score of naive bayes classifier: {:.2f}'.format(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)))
# We can see the optimal hyperparameters for the model, and adjust the grid parameter ranges for re-running if appropriate.
print('Naive Bayes best hyperparameters: {}'.format(mnb_cv.best_params_))
# Looking at the confusion matrix for the model, we can observe how well it predicted over the test set
print('Confusion matrix:\n', confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, labels=['misinfo','no_misinfo']))

Outcomes and Conclusion

There are several issues worth addressing about this project.

Firstly, there is an issue around the class imbalance of test data. Whilst this was accounted for in the training set using SMOTE, the minority target class of misinformation means that despite a high accuracy score, the classifier missed 40% of misinformation tweets in the test set. This could potentially be addressed in further study by using different scoring metrics to assess the models, to penalise missed 'misinfo', such as using the recall score instead.

With regards to the SMOTE-NC tool, whilst this was useful for balancing the target class, categorical variables were only input for the engineered features excluding the word vectors. This is an issue with using this in conjunction with the count vectorizer, as only integer values should appear in the word vectors, but SMOTE could have synthesised decimal values, giving sub-optimal model performance.

Model performance was fairly good, peaking at ~80% accuracy, but there was evidence of overfitting and only linear and naive bayes models were tested. To take this work further, additional models could be tried, for example support vector machines.

To improve performance, an improvement could include lemmatizing the tokens before vectorizing - this can sometimes cause issues around loss of meaning, but it would be worth trying in further study. Additionally, whilst POS-tagging was used here, named entity recognition could be used in conjunction to generate additional metrics.

Despite there being room for improvement, the utility of the classifier is only as good as the data fed into it. We cannot be certain that tweets were categorised correctly, and the dataset was fairly small, meaning that categories had to be merged into the 2 classifying labels used.

There could easily be bias in the categorisation process or even in the sentiment anaysis metrics used. Saif Mohammed, who has helped to design several sentiment analysis lexicons and tools, has shown that cultural, racial and gender differences can all affect how sentiment is judged (http://www.saifmohammad.com/WebDocs/Saif-2019-EIAI-talk-web.pdf). This could have affected the sentiment analysis features, but also the categorisation of the dataset, potentially limiting the utility of this tool.

However, overall this project was quite successful, and a useable classifier was found.
